<br>
First off, I usually take care of summoned items for people to start with; arrows, coldstones, and shurikens.<br>
<br>
I always use group damage shield, which doesn't effect FD one bit.  (If a mob hits an FD person, it's only because 1), it cast a spell, or 2) it wasn't fooled, so either way, the DS didn't effect the outcome).  I use group DS.  Most people are under the assumption that if you are hit with a DS up, it adds to your agro, but it's not true, so putting a DS on your enchanter is actually a good idea.  (you are aware that no one is assigned the damage of a DS, there for no one is assigned the agro from it either).<br>
<br>
When mobs are pulled, I put malosi on everything if they have medium to high resistances.  However, I don't always put malosi on, sometimes it's just wasted mana, since no one is getting resists anyways.<br>
<br>
If we get 4 or more mobs on one pull, we then go to our AE strategy, sometimes begging for large pulls.  With AE, I and another wizard, possibly more will AE nuke in the middle of the crowd while our enchanter AE stuns.  We handle anywhere from 4-8 mobs this way in a single group and boy does it add excitement.<br>
<br>
If we have a strong tank, I will nuke enough to keep myself at about 70% mana, and feed the cleric mod rods when or if (s)he gets low on mana.  The reason I use mod rods more than nuking, is that your tank can take one hell of a beating and the mana used to heal him is more effecient, than how much you shorten the battle.<br>
<br>
When in a group with a weak tank, I'll try to manage my mana to equal what the healer has.  Both of us are going to have to med after the battles, so being even makes us ready at the same time.<br>
<br>
Should our cleric or enchanter run low on mana, I always make mod rods, and ask our hybrids to heal them when they can.  I've helped hold a position many times with mod rods where most groups evac.  Sometimes, should we just have a weak tank, then I'll try to nuke things down fast instead, if I feel I can finish off what we are doing.<br>
<br>
Now, if we happen to loose our enchanter on a large pull, for what ever reason (not prepaired for AE, LD, or just agroed on before she can stun), I switch my gears.  At this point I mana burn as fast as I can (without getting agroing the mob) to eliminate mobs fast.  I'll drop to 20% mana just as fast as I can.  This reduces numbers in the fight, which will save your clerics mana (less time spent with 4+ mobs attacking everyone).  At the same time, I usually put my pet on it's own mob, but not always, sometimes our cleric or paladin will use root to effective take a mob out of the fight.  Other times all the mobs are focused on the tanks and won't fight the pet back, at which point I just put the pet on the tanks target (to quickly eliminate a mob).<br>
<br>
